{"cursor":"17640","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox disease\n|  Name = Beriberi Image = Beriberi_USNLM.jpg Caption = A sufferer â turn of the\n|  20th century in southeast Asia DiseasesDB = 14107 ICD10 = ICD9 = ICDO = OMIM\n|  = MedlinePlus = 000339 eMedicineSubj = ped eMedicineTopic = 229\n|  eMedicine_mult = MeshID = D001602\n}}\n\n'Beriberi' is the historical name of a disease caused primarily by the lack of\nVitamin B  1 (thiamine) and having two different clinical pictures in\nadults and also another profile in newborn infants of mothers with vitamin B1\ndeficiency. It is a name that was used before knowing their common nature with\nWernickeÂ´s encephalopathy.\n\nBeriberi manifested itself when food was insufficient, incomplete, or kept for\nlong. It was endemic in some regions highly dependent on rice when mechanical\npolishing of the original whole grain (brown rice) became widespread, leading to\nconsumption only of rice with the bran layer and germ removed (white rice).\nThese layers are precisely where the main deposits of thiamine are found in the\nrice grain.\n\nIn those nutritutional circumstances, in those cultural settings, and in\npopulations with particular genetic profiles, when were expressed the peculiar\nsymptomatic presentations, that then received this denomination.\n\nCurrently this disease is included within the multiple symptomatic presentations\nof Wernicke's encephalopathy (or WernickeÂ´s disease) and is maintained the use\nof the term \"beriberi\" to emphasize cardio-circulatory\ndisturbances. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/20943242\n","linknr":379,"url":"Beriberi","recorded":1371247902,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Beriberi&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Beriberi&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/